<TITLE> UN chief set to fly in </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 1 (bdnews24.com)  UN secretary-general Ban Ki-moon is set to arrive in the city Saturday afternoon on a two-day official visit. He will meet the leaders of the BNP and the Awami League Sunday to discuss Bangladesh's return to democracy through the Dec 18 general elections. Ban, who will be the fourth UN chief to visit Bangladesh, is also scheduled to meet president Iajuddin Ahmed, chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed and foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury. Earlier, Kurt Waldheim, Javier Perez de Cuellar and Kofi Annan visited Bangladesh. According to his itinerary, Ban will meet the foreign adviser on Saturday evening and attend a dinner hosted by the chief adviser in his honour. On Sunday, he will place floral wreath at the National Memorial at Savar in the morning and fly to Sirajganj and Bogra to see a UNDP project and a Grameen Bank programme respectively. The secretary-general is scheduled to meet Iajuddin, Fakhruddin and the AL and BNP leaders in the afternoon. He will leave Bangladesh on Sunday night for the UN headquarters in New York after holding a press conference at Hotel Sonargaon at 6pm. Ban, a Korean national, will also attend a dinner at the residence of Korean ambassador in Dhaka. bd
